#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Fake kubectl for tests and demos: a scriptable Percona-PG-Operator cluster.

State lives in $FAKE_KUBE_STATE/state.json (auto-seeded on first call) and
evolves with time so scenarios play out like a real cluster:

* ``exec ... kill -9`` (Case B / pgkill): leader postgres restarts in place —
  probe fails and Patroni shows state=starting for FAKE_KUBE_RESTART_S, then
  recovers. Leader name and TL unchanged (the classification lesson).
* ``delete pod <leader>`` (Case C1): the pod vanishes for FAKE_KUBE_RECREATE_S
  then returns Running; restart-in-place by default, election if
  FAKE_KUBE_C1_ELECT=1.
* ``exec ... patronictl switchover`` (Case A): leader moves to the first
  replica, TL bumps, probe blips for FAKE_KUBE_SWITCH_BLIP_S.
* ``delete node`` / ``cordon`` (Case C2): pods on the node vanish; a replica
  is elected after FAKE_KUBE_ELECT_S; TL bumps.
* ``exec ... pgbackrest backup``: holds the stanza lock for FAKE_KUBE_BACKUP_S
  (a second backup gets the field-famous rc=50 in 0.1s); archive queue depth
  ramps while running. FAKE_KUBE_BACKUP_LOCKED=1 pins the lock (preflight
  abort tests).

Everything prints in the real formats the parsers expect (patronictl JSON,
pgbackrest info text, kubectl -o json).
"""
